@NODE Intro "Introduction"

                                  ..
                             .---:  :---------.
                             |   ṖṖṖṖ         |
                            [%] iNTRODUCTiON [%]
                             |         ....   |
                             `---------:  :---'
                                        ṖṖ

A  dinky good looking little FAME lastcallers utility that will produce the
following outputs:

	Ṗ last callers with up to 20 users
	Ṗ weekly statistics
	Ṗ system records
	Ṗ mini callers log
@ENDNODE
@NODE Install "Installation"

                                  ..
                             .---:  :---------.
                             |   ṖṖṖṖ         |
                            [%] iNSTALLATiON [%]
                             |         ....   |
                             `---------:  :---'
                                        ṖṖ

Put V-LastCallers into a directory within your DOORS:  assign.  The obvious
choice would be a dir called "V-LASTCALLERS" or something similar :)

Put the 3 header files in the same dir as the program, the files are:

	Ṗ LCHeader.TXT - Last Callers header file
	Ṗ WSHeader.TXT - Week Stats header file
	Ṗ RSHeader.TXT - Record Stats header file

The program will look in PROGDIR: for all it's header/data files.

To make the lastcallers door update at every logoff put a copy of the
LastCallers.Script file in FAME:Node{x}/NodeBatches/LogoffBatches/
where {x} is the number of your modem node(s).

So if you have 2 modem nodes then put a copy of the script in each one.

If the script is missing then it should look like...

------------------------------------------------------------------
.key node
.bra {
.ket }

DOORS:V-TOOLS/V-LastCallers/LastCallers {node} 10 SCREENS:BULLS/VLC_LASTCALLERS.TXT SCREENS:BULLS/VLC_WEEKSTATS.TXT SCREENS:BULLS/VLC_RECORDSTATS.TXT FAME:Mini_Callers.Log
------------------------------------------------------------------

obviously the paths will be different for your system.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage "Usage"

                               ..
                          .---:  :--------------.
                          |   ṖṖṖṖ              |
                         [%] USiNG THE PROGRAM [%]
                          |              ....   |
                          `--------------:  :---'
                                          ṖṖ

Usage: LastCallers <node> <lines> <LCFile> <WSFile> <RSFile> <MCLFile>

<node>    : the node to update for
<lines>   : the number of users in the LastCallers output file
<LCFile>  : filename to save LastCallers bulletin as
<WSFile>  : filename to save WeeklyStats bulletin as
<RSFile>  : filename to save RecordStats bulletin as
<MCLFile> : filename to save MiniCallersLog as

e.g.

LastCallers 1 10 BULLS:LAST10 BULLS:WEEKLY BULLS:RECORDS FAME:MINI.LOG
@ENDNODE
@NODE Structures "Structures"

                                ..
                           .---:  :-------.
                           |   ṖṖṖṖ       |
                          [%] STRUCTURES [%]
                           |       ....   |
                           `-------:  :---'
                                    ṖṖ

To  allow  other  programmers  to  re-use  the  data files stored here, the
following  structures have been included.  At time of writing FAME does not
write  details  of  messages  written/comments  to sysop, therefore certain
items in the structure are marked as *NOT USED*, if FAME starts writing the
details to the callerslog these items will be filled.


                  @{"  " LINK "LastCallers.DAT"} LastCallers.DAT - 20 Last Callers
                  @{"  " LINK "Days.DAT"} Days.DAT        - Last weeks stats
                  @{"  " LINK "Records.DAT"} Records.DAT     - System Records
@ENDNODE
@NODE LastCallers.DAT "LastCallers.DAT"

Structure of an entry in LastCallers.DAT - there are 20 of these in the
file, the first is the latest logoff.

struct CLStats
{
    int     nodenumber,         // Node number
            logontype;          // Type of logon             *DEFINES BELOW*
    char    logondate[9],       // Date in fomat MM-DD-YY
            logontime[9];       // Time in format HH:MM:SS
    int     userslot;           // FAME slot number
    char    username[32],       // FAME User name
            userloc[32],        // FAME User location
            logoffdate[9],      // Date in fomat MM-DD-YY
            logofftime[9];      // Time in format HH:MM:SS
    int     timeon,             // Time online in mins
            logofftype,         // Type of logoff            *DEFINES BELOW*
            speed,              // Connect speed (baud rate)
            confjoins,          // Number of confs joined, inc auto-rejoin
            fileviews,          // Number of files viewed (menu command V)
            pwfails,            // Number of password fails, inc system & NUP
            dirscans,           // Number of dir scans inc newfiles scans
            msgwrite,           // Number of messages written.    *NOT USED*
            msgread,            // Number of times cmd R used.    *NOT USED*
            pages,              // Number of times the sysop was paged
            comments,           // Number of times cmd C used.    *NOT USED*
            ealls,              // Number of EALLs written        *NOT USED*
            newuser,            // Is the user a newuser        0=NO 1=YES
            sysopchats,         // Number of times user chatted to sysop
            changestats,        // Number of times command W was used
            sys_accountedits,   // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '1' was used
            sys_clogviews,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '2' was used
            sys_udlogviews,     // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '3' was used
            sys_doorlogviews,   // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '4' was used
            sys_listedits,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '5' was used
            sys_fileedits,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '6' was used
            sys_doslists,       // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '7' was used
            sys_dosdirs,        // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '8' was used
            sys_dosinfos,       // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '9' was used
            sys_shells,         // SYSOP - Number of times 'SHELL' was used
            ul_files,           // Number of files uploaded
            ul_kbytes,          // Size of uploads (in KB)
            dl_files,           // Number of files downloaded
            dl_kbytes;          // Size of downloads (in KB)
    char    sparespace[40];     // Space for later expansion
};

/*----------------------( Defines for type of logon )----------------------*/
#define LOGON_UNKNOWN    0                          // Fallback value
#define LOGON_MODEM      1                          // Normal modem connect
#define LOGON_RELOGON    2                          // ReLogon (RL from menu)
#define LOGON_SYSOP      3                          // F1 or SF1
#define LOGON_LOCAL      4                          // F2 or SF2
/*--------------------( Defines for type of logoff )-----------------------*/
#define LOGOFF_UNKNOWN   0                          // Fallback value
#define LOGOFF_NORMAL    1                          // Normal (G from menu)
#define LOGOFF_TIMEOUT   2                          // Door & Node timeout
#define LOGOFF_RELOGON   3                          // ReLogon (RL from menu)
#define LOGOFF_KICK      4                          // User kicked (F10)
#define LOGOFF_TIMELIM   5                          // User timelimit reached
#define LOGOFF_CARRIER   6                          // User lost carrier
@ENDNODE
@NODE Days.DAT "Days.DAT"

Structure of an entry in Days.DAT - there are 8 records in the file.
The first is the current day and is still being filled with each call,
the second is yesterday, the third is the day before yesterday etc etc

struct DayStats
{
    char    lastupdate[9];      // Date of last update (MM-DD-YY)
    int     calls,              // Number of calls
            mins,               // Number of mins in use
            confjoins,          // Number of join confs (inc auto-rejoin)
            fileviews,          // Number of files viewed (menu command V)
            pwfails,            // Number of password fails, inc system & NUP
            dirscans,           // Number of dir scans inc newfiles scans
            msgwrite,           // Number of messages written.    *NOT USED*
            msgread,            // Number of times cmd R used.    *NOT USED*
            pages,              // Number of times the sysop was paged
            comments,           // Number of times cmd C used.    *NOT USED*
            ealls,              // Number of EALLs written        *NOT USED*
            newusers,           // Number of new users
            sysopchats,         // Number of times user chatted to sysop
            changestats,        // Number of times command W was used
            sys_accountedits,   // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '1' was used
            sys_clogviews,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '2' was used
            sys_udlogviews,     // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '3' was used
            sys_doorlogviews,   // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '4' was used
            sys_listedits,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '5' was used
            sys_fileedits,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '6' was used
            sys_doslists,       // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '7' was used
            sys_dosdirs,        // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '8' was used
            sys_dosinfos,       // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '9' was used
            sys_shells,         // SYSOP - Number of times 'SHELL' was used
            ul_files,           // Number of files uploaded
            ul_kbytes,          // Size of uploads (in KB)
            dl_files,           // Number of files downloaded
            dl_kbytes,          // Size of downloads (in KB)
            lostcarriers;       // Number of lost carriers
    char    sparespace[36];     // Space for later expansion
};
@ENDNODE
@NODE Records.DAT "Records.DAT"

Structure of the system records file, the dates are in standard C format
(number of seconds since Jan 1st 1970 or whatever it is).

struct SystemRecords
{
    int     calls,              calls_date,             // Number of calls
            mins,               mins_date,              // Number of mins in use
            confjoins,          confjoins_date,         // Number of join confs (inc auto-rejoin)
            fileviews,          fileviews_date,         // Number of files viewed (menu command V)
            pwfails,            pwfails_date,           // Number of password fails, inc system & NUP
            dirscans,           dirscans_date,          // Number of dir scans inc newfiles scans
            msgwrite,           msgwrite_date,          // Number of messages written.    *NOT USED*
            msgread,            msgread_date,           // Number of times cmd R used.    *NOT USED*
            pages,              pages_date,             // Number of times the sysop was paged
            comments,           comments_date,          // Number of times cmd C used.    *NOT USED*
            ealls,              ealls_date,             // Number of EALLs written        *NOT USED*
            newusers,           newusers_date,          // Number of new users
            sysopchats,         sysopchats_date,        // Number of times user chatted to sysop
            changestats,        changestats_date,       // Number of times command W was used
            sys_accountedits,   sys_accountedits_date,  // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '1' was used
            sys_clogviews,      sys_clogviews_date,     // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '2' was used
            sys_udlogviews,     sys_udlogviews_date,    // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '3' was used
            sys_doorlogviews,   sys_doorlogviews_date,  // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '4' was used
            sys_listedits,      sys_listedits_date,     // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '5' was used
            sys_fileedits,      sys_fileedits_date,     // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '6' was used
            sys_doslists,       sys_doslists_date,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '7' was used
            sys_dosdirs,        sys_dosdirs_date,       // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '8' was used
            sys_dosinfos,       sys_dosinfos_date,      // SYSOP - Number of times cmd '9' was used
            sys_shells,         sys_shells_date,        // SYSOP - Number of times 'SHELL' was used
            ul_files,           ul_files_date,          // Number of files uploaded
            ul_kbytes,          ul_kbytes_date,         // Size of uploads (in KB)
            dl_files,           dl_files_date,          // Number of files downloaded
            dl_kbytes,          dl_kbytes_date,         // Size of downloads (in KB)
            lostcarriers,       lostcarriers_date;      // Number of lost carriers
    char    sparespace[32];                             // Space for later expansion
};
@ENDNODE
